## Table 2

Blood pressure according to titration groups

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} = systolic blood pressure; {{ drug.molecular_formula }} = diastolic blood pressure.

*

P values between the groups <.001 for all.

Blood pressure control in this study was defined as a value <140/90 mm Hg based on the criteria of the Sixth Report of the Joint National Committee on the Prevention, Detection, Evaluation and Treatment of High Blood Pressure ({{ drug.molecular_formula }} VI).9Table 3 shows the control rates (as percentages) for all patients as well as groups of elderly and African Americans at initial and maximal dosing. It should be noted that in general for the lower dose ({{ drug.strength }}) group, fewer than 100% of patients were controlled at visit 2; this indicates that in some cases physicians elected not to increase the drug dose although it was required by the study protocol. Indeed, the protocol required that any value >130/85 mm Hg would require uptitration, suggesting that a reasonably large number of patients with {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} substantially greater than that threshold, in fact, did not get titrated to the 80-mg dose. It can also be seen in Table 3 that a small proportion of patients who were titrated to the 80-mg dose actually were controlled at the {{ drug.strength }} dose; this can be partly explained by the fact that these patients may have had blood pressures >130/85 mm Hg but <140/90 mm Hg at visit 2.

